Yosemite on film 🎞️. I’ve grown to enjoy film a lot more lately. I rarely pick up my digital camera, unless it’s something extraordinary or for client work.

I think its a double nostalgia thing: 1) I don’t develop right away- and when I do, its like viewing a time capsule. 2) it just looks…so different. If you’ve been following me for a while, you know I love to edit my digitals in clean, punchy contrast. I usually leave my film photos alone (aside from some minor brightness/shadows)!

Dear Ryder,

I wont be able to give you a normal doggie life. You wont have your local dog park to run at. And…you wont have your own backyard to call your home.

But what I can give you is a life of adventure. From the deserts of the southwest, to the forests of the PNW, and everywhere in between. Infinite trails to run. Infinite sights to see. Infinite places to call home. Welcome to roadlife Ryder 🐶!

Ryder is now the Dryver. 🛻 🥁

Life has been puppy filled lately! Im actually taking a break from living on the road at the moment - for the first time in almost 3 years! Staying at a couple airbnbs, catching up on life, and adjusting myself to having a companion on the road. 

Tbh, I needed a break regardless - SUV living is quite taxing. So for now, enjoying some weekend adventures, a roof and walls, daily showers, and dealing with potty training.

Thx for snapping a pic of me and Ryder @johanna.hendrickson (2nd shot) !

I’ve waited so long to be financially and physically available to raise a dog responsibly. Oddly enough, now is that time. Working remotely and traveling allows me to show my pup the world!

New house who dis? I just picked up this 99’ Toyota Tacoma with a 77’ chinook pop-up camper conversion!

I’ve been thinking about getting a larger rig for a long time now. Tossing the idea between a new truck/camper, sprinter, airstream, jdm rv, and everything in between. I saw this beauty for sale the other week and I knew I had to get it!

I’ll give a full tour in the coming week, but too excited to share! And no I’m not selling my GX. It’s going to be parked in storage for a while.

We moved out of the Lexus GX470 and into this ‘99 Toyota Tacoma / ‘77 Chinook camper! It has WAY more room for the both of us, and its quite cozy! And yes, I’m keeping the Lexus.

#overlanding #gx470 #tacoma #chinook #tacomaoffroad #tacomanation #smalltruckcampers #truckcamper #overlanding4x4 #australianshepherd #australianshepherdpuppy

This home has become huge part of my life. Yes, I did move out of it. And yes, I’m keeping it. 

📸 🎞️ : @nathanielfilm 

I’ve had the GX for almost 3 years now and is hands down my favorite vehicle - because its my home. Because its brought me on so many adventures and helped me make so many friends.

I’ve wanted to get a second rig for over a year now - living out of a SUV takes its toll on you. So much so, I put content creation on the back burner to focus on work, living, and enjoying life.

I’m hoping I can get back into the swing of things with the new rig. More comfort. More time to slow down. More time to create.

*I’ve had numerous inquiries about me selling it. If I ever do, please be aware it won’t be cheap. Between the replaced engine, trans, and all the gear I’ve invested close to $50k. Not including the vehicle cost. It’s going to be in storage for a while, occasionally living in it at times. But I’m probably going to convert it to more of a true offroad rig (35/37s, lockers…) once I “retire” from full-time roadlife.

99’ Toyota Tacoma + 77’ Chinook camper. It’s a one of a kind, but it has some quirks.

It’s time to tear into this thing. I bought the Tacoma with the intentions of keeping it as-is for a while, but after owning it for the past few months, I’ve got the itch to make it mine.

I’ve got a one month deadline to strip the interior, add insulation, fix leaks, new flooring, cabinetry and appliances. On top of that…some external offroad mods are in order. Will be documenting the entire progress, so content on here might change a bit! (for the better). Stay tuned!

#ad If there’s one thing I’d recommend for working remotely, it would be a weBoost. While it won’t magically find cell signal in a dead zone, it will often boost a couple bars of service. That little boost could be the difference between slow internet, and fast-enough for work! Check out the link in my bio for the @amazon Drive Into the Outdoors Event page where you can find the weBoost and a whole lot more of outdoor automotive products. #AmazonAutomotive #AmazonFinds

Through the larches 🌲🛻. 

Larches are of the few (if not only?) deciduous conifer trees , meaning their needles change color in the fall. And while you can find shorter larches in high alpine mountains, these massive 100ft larches are scattered in spots throughout the US.

--- 
Every fall since i've been on the road, I've always headed back south to the desert to avoid the rain - roadlife sucks in the rain. Primarily because everything stays wet and it's hard to dry off clothes, and even yourself. 

But this winter is going to look a bit different. I'm staying back in the PNW and embracing the moody weather and searching for more powder ❄️, here in the states and across the border 🇨🇦. Theres a lot more to this stay, but I'll catch ya'll up on that when the time comes.
🍑. Flying down south this week and freeing the GX from retirement. So many things planned for this thing in the coming months 🛠️
Aussies are one of the smartest dogs, but did you know they can drive too? 🐶🛻

Thankful for life. Thankful for Ryder. Thankful for friends and family. Thankful for all of you.

It's been a bit hectic lately. for a while now actually. I have 6 months of backlogged photos/videos and haven't had much time to edit. But I promise I'll catch ya'll up very soon. If you've made it this far reading this caption, the last picture is a hint at the HUGE changes that have been happening behind the scenes. Very, very excited for what's to come.

Is this end of roadlife? For now.

I think there's a balance when roadlife makes sense, and I've been fighting the urge to stop for about a year now. There's a lot I want to accomplish right now in my life and living on the road is eating up precious time. 

And one of those things is to take content creation more seriously. Adventures will have more purpose, and I'll be able to immerse myself instead of worrying about roadlife logistics. I'm really excited to experiment with my content as well.

So yeah. I'm stoked!
